name: num::error::IntErrorKind

VariantIdx(Some(0))-FieldIdx(None).name: Empty
VariantIdx(Some(0))-FieldIdx(None).doc:
Value being parsed is empty.

 This variant will be constructed when parsing an empty string.

VariantIdx(Some(1))-FieldIdx(None).name: InvalidDigit
VariantIdx(Some(1))-FieldIdx(None).doc:
Contains an invalid digit in its context.

 Among other causes, this variant will be constructed when parsing a string that
 contains a non-ASCII char.

 This variant is also constructed when a `+` or `-` is misplaced within a string
 either on its own or in the middle of a number.

VariantIdx(Some(2))-FieldIdx(None).name: PosOverflow
VariantIdx(Some(2))-FieldIdx(None).doc: Integer is too large to store in target integer type.

VariantIdx(Some(3))-FieldIdx(None).name: NegOverflow
VariantIdx(Some(3))-FieldIdx(None).doc: Integer is too small to store in target integer type.

VariantIdx(Some(4))-FieldIdx(None).name: Zero
VariantIdx(Some(4))-FieldIdx(None).doc:
Value was Zero

 This variant will be emitted when the parsing string has a value of zero, which
 would be illegal for non-zero types.
